---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Lineage | Grithos"
  description="The philosophical lineage of Grithos — how Marcus Aurelius, Epictetus, and Benjamin Franklin laid the foundation centuries ago. Ancient wisdom mapped to the four pillars."
  ogTitle="The Lineage — Grithos"
  ogDescription="Before Grithos, there was Marcus, Epictetus, and Franklin. Ancient wisdom mapped to the four pillars. The roots of a modern philosophy."
  ogUrl="https://grithos.com/lineage"
  canonical="https://grithos.com/lineage"
  activePage="lineage"
>

<style is:inline>
  /* ═══ PAGE HERO ═══ */
  .page-hero {
    padding: 160px 0 80px;
    text-align: center;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .page-hero::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    top: 40%; left: 50%; transform: translateX(-50%);
    width: 800px; height: 800px;
    background: radial-gradient(circle, rgba(201,147,90,.05) 0%, transparent 70%);
    pointer-events: none;
    z-index: 0;
  }
  .page-hero .wrap { position: relative; z-index: 1; }
  .page-hero-overline {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 10px;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: .18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--gold);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .page-hero-title {
    font-family: var(--heading);
    font-size: clamp(32px, 4vw, 52px);
    font-weight: 800;
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -.02em;
    color: var(--white);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .page-hero-sub {
    font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: clamp(16px, 2vw, 20px);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  /* ═══ SECTION DIVIDER ═══ */
  .section-divider {
    width: 100%;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--border);
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ═══ INTRO ═══ */
  .intro {
    padding: 80px 0;
  }
  .intro-text {
    font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.9;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .intro-text p + p {
    margin-top: 20px;
  }

  /* ═══ PILLAR SECTION ═══ */
  .lineage-section {
    padding: 100px 0;
  }
  .lineage-header {
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 60px;
  }
  .lineage-pillar-label {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 10px;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: .18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--gold);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .lineage-pillar-name {
    font-family: var(--heading);
    font-size: clamp(24px, 3vw, 36px);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--white);
    letter-spacing: -.01em;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .lineage-pillar-tagline {
    font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: 16px;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  /* ═══ QUOTE PAIR ═══ */
  .quote-pair {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 0 0 56px;
  }
  .quote-pair + .quote-pair {
    padding-top: 56px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  /* Marcus quote */
  .marcus-quote {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--gold);
    padding: 0 0 0 24px;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }
  .marcus-quote p {
    font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: 17px;
    font-style: italic;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--white);
  }
  .marcus-cite {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: .08em;
    color: var(--gold);
    padding-left: 27px;
    margin-bottom: 28px;
  }

  /* Bridge text */
  .bridge {
    font-family: var(--body);
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }
  .bridge strong {
    color: var(--white);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* ═══ FIGURE HEADER ═══ */
  .figure-header {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 auto 48px;
    padding-top: 56px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .figure-header:first-of-type {
    padding-top: 0;
    border-top: none;
  }
  .figure-name {
    font-family: var(--heading);
    font-size: clamp(18px, 2.2vw, 22px);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--white);
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
  .figure-years {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: .08em;
    color: var(--gold);
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }
  .figure-intro {
    font-family: var(--body);
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    max-width: 760px;
  }

  /* ═══ CLOSING ═══ */
  .closing {
    padding: 100px 0 120px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .closing-text {
    font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: clamp(20px, 2.8vw, 28px);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--white);
    line-height: 1.5;
    max-width: 700px;
    margin: 0 auto 24px;
  }
  .closing-sub {
    font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
    font-size: clamp(15px, 2vw, 18px);
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  /* ═══ BACK LINK ═══ */
  .back-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    font-family: var(--body);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: color .2s;
    margin-top: 48px;
  }
  .back-link:hover { color: var(--gold); }
  .back-link svg { width: 16px; height: 16px; }

  /* ═══ RESPONSIVE ═══ */
  @media(max-width:768px) {
    .lineage-section { padding: 60px 0; }
    .quote-pair { padding: 0 0 40px; }
    .quote-pair + .quote-pair { padding-top: 40px; }
  }
</style>

<!-- ═══ HERO ═══ -->
<section class="page-hero">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal d1">
      <p class="page-hero-overline">The Lineage</p>
      <h1 class="page-hero-title">The Lineage</h1>
      <p class="page-hero-sub">Grithos did not invent its truths. A Roman Emperor, a former slave, and a founding father lived them first. Their words prove these principles are timeless.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══ INTRO ═══ -->
<section class="intro">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="reveal d1">
      <div class="intro-text">
        <p>Marcus Aurelius was the Emperor of Rome. Epictetus was born a slave. Benjamin Franklin was a self-made printer who helped build a nation. Three men. Three centuries apart. All of them lived the same truths that Grithos now carries forward.</p>
        <p>Grithos did not invent its principles. It inherited them. The ideas that form the Four Pillars have been tested across millennia — by emperors and slaves, by founders and ordinary people trying to live well. What Grithos does is name them, sharpen them, and make them a daily practice.</p>
        <p>This is not a religion. It is a philosophy with ancient roots and a God who authored the structure we live within. What follows is the thread that connects the lineage to Grithos — proof that these truths are not new. They are timeless.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══ VIRTUE ═══ -->
<section class="lineage-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="lineage-header reveal d1">
      <p class="lineage-pillar-label">Pillar I — Virtue</p>
      <h2 class="lineage-pillar-name">Do Right Regardless</h2>
      <p class="lineage-pillar-tagline">What they wrote about honesty and moral courage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d2">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Marcus Aurelius</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">121 – 180 AD · Emperor of Rome</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Never esteem anything as of advantage to you that will make you break your word or lose your self-respect.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book III</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet II — <strong>Keep Your Word Like Your Life Depends on It.</strong> Marcus understood that no advantage gained through broken promises is worth the cost. A Grithosian treats their word as sacred. Not because someone is watching — because your integrity is the one thing no one can take from you unless you surrender it.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Waste no more time arguing about what a good man should be. Be one.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book X</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the heart of Grithos Virtue — <strong>do right, regardless.</strong> Marcus had no patience for philosophizing about goodness without living it. Neither does Grithos. The tenets are not ideas to discuss. They are practices to live. Every single day.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>If it is not right do not do it; if it is not true do not say it.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book XII</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet I — <strong>Tell the Truth. Even When It Costs You.</strong> Marcus reduced virtue to its simplest form: right action, honest speech. No exceptions. No qualifiers. Nearly two thousand years later, Grithos says the same thing. Some truths never change.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d5">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The object of life is not to be on the side of the majority, but to escape finding oneself in the ranks of the insane.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book IV</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet II — <strong>Keep Your Word Like Your Life Depends on It.</strong> Marcus knew that the crowd will always pressure you to bend. Keeping your word when everyone around you is breaking theirs is not stubbornness — it is sanity. A Grithosian does not follow the majority into compromise.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Benjamin Franklin</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1706 – 1790 · Founding Father, Inventor, Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>He that is good for making excuses is seldom good for anything else.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet III — <strong>Own Your Wins. But Do Right in the Dark.</strong> Franklin had no patience for people who explained away their failures instead of owning them. A Grithosian does not make excuses. When something goes wrong and it was your fault — say so. Fix what can be fixed. Learn what can be learned. Excuses are the language of people who have given up on themselves.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Well done is better than well said.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the soul of Virtue — action over words. Franklin did not just talk about being a good man. He tracked his own character daily in a notebook. A Grithosian does the same. The Daily Practice is not philosophy to read. It is philosophy to live.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Epictetus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">50 – 135 AD · Former Slave, Stoic Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Make the best use of what is in your power, and take the rest as it happens.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book I</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet I — <strong>Tell the Truth. Even When It Costs You.</strong> Epictetus understood that doing right means acting on what you control — your honesty, your integrity, your choices — and releasing what you cannot control. The reaction belongs to the other person. The truth belongs to you.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══ STRENGTH / APEX ═══ -->
<section class="lineage-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="lineage-header reveal d1">
      <p class="lineage-pillar-label">Pillar II — Apex</p>
      <h2 class="lineage-pillar-name">Own Your Nature</h2>
      <p class="lineage-pillar-tagline">What they wrote about human strength and responsibility.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d2">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Marcus Aurelius</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">121 – 180 AD · Emperor of Rome</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>You have power over your mind — not outside events. Realize this, and you will find strength.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book VI</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the foundation of Apex. Marcus knew that true strength is not found in controlling the world around you — it is found in owning yourself completely. A Grithosian does not shrink. A Grithosian does not apologize for their strength. Because that strength comes from within, and no outside event can take it.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Accept the things to which fate binds you, and love the people with whom fate brings you together, and do so with all your heart.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book VI</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet V — <strong>Protect Those Beneath You.</strong> Marcus understood that apex is not isolation. It is connection. The strongest person in the room has the deepest obligation to love and protect those around them. Power without protection is tyranny. Marcus knew this as Emperor. Grithos makes it a tenet.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The impediment to action advances action. What stands in the way becomes the way.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book V</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VI — <strong>Reject the Victim. Become the Author.</strong> Marcus did not see obstacles as punishments. He saw them as raw material. Every hardship is an opportunity to demonstrate your apex nature. A Grithosian does not ask "why me?" A Grithosian asks "what now?" The obstacle is not in the way. It is the way.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Epictetus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">50 – 135 AD · Former Slave, Stoic Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">Born into slavery in Hierapolis, Epictetus endured a broken leg at the hands of his master and emerged as one of the greatest Stoic philosophers who ever lived. His teachings, recorded by his student Arrian in the Discourses, became the primary texts Marcus Aurelius studied. A man who owned nothing — not even his own body — and yet mastered everything within his control.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>No man is free who is not master of himself.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the soul of Apex. Epictetus was legally owned by another human being — and yet he was freer than most people who have ever lived. Because freedom is not about external circumstances. It is about internal sovereignty. A Grithosian does not wait for permission to be strong. Strength is claimed from within, regardless of what the world puts on you.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>It's not what happens to you, but how you react to it that matters.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VI — <strong>Reject the Victim. Become the Author.</strong> Epictetus lived this tenet before it had a name. His leg was broken. His freedom was stripped. He did not become a victim. He became the teacher whose words shaped an emperor. Your circumstances do not define you. Your response does.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>First say to yourself what you would be; and then do what you have to do.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book III</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IV — <strong>Never Shrink. Never Apologize for Strength.</strong> Epictetus understood that apex begins with identity. You must first decide who you are — then act accordingly. Do not shrink to fit rooms that are too small for you. Decide what you would be, and then become it through daily, relentless action.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Benjamin Franklin</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1706 – 1790 · Founding Father, Inventor, Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Energy and persistence conquer all things.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IV — <strong>Never Shrink. Never Apologize for Strength.</strong> Franklin was not born powerful. He built his strength through relentless persistence — failed experiments, rejected proposals, years of quiet work. A Grithosian knows that strength is not a gift. It is persistence made visible. Keep going.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══ CONTROL ═══ -->
<section class="lineage-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="lineage-header reveal d1">
      <p class="lineage-pillar-label">Pillar III — Control</p>
      <h2 class="lineage-pillar-name">Live Within Bounds</h2>
      <p class="lineage-pillar-tagline">What they wrote about what is yours and what is not.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d2">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Marcus Aurelius</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">121 – 180 AD · Emperor of Rome</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>You always own the option of having no opinion. There is never any need to get worked up or to trouble your soul about things you can't control.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book VI</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Marcus drew the same line that Grithos draws: your thoughts, your decisions, your effort, your character. Everything else belongs to the bounds. But where Marcus counseled calm acceptance, Grithos adds fire — you own what is yours, you fight for the outcome, and only when the bounds truly close the door do you redirect.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The universe is change; our life is what our thoughts make it.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book IV</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VIII — <strong>Redirect Immediately.</strong> Marcus understood that the universe does not pause for your grief, your outrage, or your plans. It changes. Constantly. A Grithosian does not waste energy fighting change. You redirect — immediately, deliberately — toward what you can actually influence. The bounds are not your enemy. They are the structure God authored, and they are trustworthy.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Everything we hear is an opinion, not a fact. Everything we see is a perspective, not the truth.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book IV</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IX — <strong>Trust the Bounds.</strong> Marcus knew that most of what troubles us is not reality — it is our interpretation of reality. The bounds are rational and consistent. God authored them that way. A Grithosian trusts the structure, even when the interpretation feels unbearable. Separate what happened from your story about what happened. The bounds hold.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Benjamin Franklin</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1706 – 1790 · Founding Father, Inventor, Philosopher</p>
      <p class="figure-intro">A self-educated printer who became a scientist, diplomat, and architect of a nation. Franklin created a system of thirteen virtues and tracked his adherence to them daily in a small notebook — the original daily practice. He understood that character is not inherited. It is built, one disciplined day at a time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>An investment in knowledge pays the best interest.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> Franklin understood that the only assets no one can take from you are the ones you build inside yourself — your knowledge, your character, your discipline. A Grithosian invests in what is truly theirs. Not possessions. Not titles. The things that compound quietly and last forever.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>By failing to prepare, you are preparing to fail.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the discipline of Pillar III — <strong>live within bounds.</strong> Franklin did not leave virtue to chance. He tracked it. Daily. In a notebook he carried everywhere. A Grithosian does the same with the Daily Practice — one practice per day, every day. Discipline is not what you do when you feel like it. It is the structure you build so you do it regardless.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>I didn't fail the test. I just found 100 ways to do it wrong.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VIII — <strong>Redirect Immediately.</strong> Franklin failed constantly — business ventures, experiments, diplomatic efforts. He did not spiral. He redirected. Every failure was data. Every closed door was a map to the next open one. A Grithosian treats failure the same way: not as a verdict, but as a pivot point.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Epictetus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">50 – 135 AD · Former Slave, Stoic Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Make the best use of what is in your power, and take the rest as it happens.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book I</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet VII — <strong>Own Only What Is Yours.</strong> This is the original statement of the control boundary. Epictetus drew the line twenty centuries ago — what is in your power and what is not. A Grithosian honors that line. You fight for everything within the bounds. You release everything outside them. That is not weakness. That is wisdom.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Man is not worried by real problems so much as by his imagined anxieties about real problems.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet IX — <strong>Trust the Bounds.</strong> Epictetus saw what anxiety really is — a war against things that haven't happened yet. The bounds are real. Your worry about the bounds is not. A Grithosian separates the actual threat from the imagined one, and works only on what is real.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══ DEATH ═══ -->
<section class="lineage-section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="lineage-header reveal d1">
      <p class="lineage-pillar-label">Pillar IV — Death</p>
      <h2 class="lineage-pillar-name">Return to the Whole</h2>
      <p class="lineage-pillar-tagline">What they wrote about mortality and legacy.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d2">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Marcus Aurelius</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">121 – 180 AD · Emperor of Rome</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>It is not death that a man should fear, but he should fear never beginning to live.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book XII</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Marcus did not fear death. He feared wasted life. A Grithosian uses mortality as the sharpest tool in the drawer — not as a threat, but as a lens. Every decision passes through it. Is this how you want to spend the time you have? If the answer is no, stop. Redirect. Now.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Loss is nothing else but change, and change is nature's delight.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book IX</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Marcus saw loss as transformation, not destruction. A Grithosian honors this — feel the grief completely, because it is proof of what you built. But do not live there. Loss is change. And change, as Marcus wrote, is woven into the fabric of existence. God authored the bounds to include both creation and loss. Trust both.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Think of yourself as dead. You have lived your life. Now, take what's left and live it properly.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book VII</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Marcus challenged himself to live as if he had already wasted his life — and now had one final chance to do it right. A Grithosian builds something that matters right here, right now. The people you lead, the truths you tell, the strength you use to protect others. That is your legacy in this life — and it matters regardless of what comes next.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d5">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>The soul becomes dyed with the color of its thoughts.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Marcus Aurelius, Meditations, Book V</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Marcus understood that legacy is not built in a single grand gesture. It is built thought by thought, day by day. What you think about shapes who you become. A Grithosian guards their thoughts the way they guard their word — because both become permanent.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Epictetus</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">50 – 135 AD · Former Slave, Stoic Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>What is death? A scary mask. Take it off — see, it doesn't bite.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book II</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet X — <strong>Live Like You Will Die. Because You Will.</strong> Epictetus stripped death of its power by refusing to dress it up in fear. A Grithosian does the same. Death is a bound — the final one. It is not a punishment. It is the structure that makes your time here matter. Use it as fuel, not as a cage.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>It is difficulties that show what men are.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Epictetus, Discourses, Book I</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XI — <strong>Grieve Fully. Then Move.</strong> Epictetus did not teach people to avoid difficulty. He taught them that difficulty is the proving ground. Grief, loss, suffering — these are not the end of the story. They are the chapter that reveals who you really are. Feel everything. Then rise.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="figure-header reveal d1">
      <h3 class="figure-name">Benjamin Franklin</h3>
      <p class="figure-years">1706 – 1790 · Founding Father, Inventor, Philosopher</p>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d2">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>If you would not be forgotten as soon as you are dead, either write things worth reading or do things worth the writing.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is Tenet XII — <strong>Build a Legacy That Stands in This Life.</strong> Franklin did both. He wrote things the world still reads and built things the world still uses. A Grithosian does not hope to be remembered. A Grithosian builds something worth remembering. Not for vanity — because the mark you leave proves you were here and it mattered.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d3">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>When you're finished changing, you're finished.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This is the urgency of Pillar IV — <strong>you are not done yet.</strong> Franklin reinvented himself constantly — printer, scientist, diplomat, founder. He never stopped building. A Grithosian understands that the moment you stop growing, you have chosen to start dying. Legacy is not something you build once. It is something you build until your last breath.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="quote-pair reveal d4">
      <blockquote class="marcus-quote">
        <p>Hide not your talents. They for use were made. What's a sundial in the shade?</p>
      </blockquote>
      <div class="marcus-cite">— Benjamin Franklin, Poor Richard's Almanack</div>
      <div class="bridge">
        This speaks to every Grithosian who feels alone or unseen. Your gifts are not for you alone. They are for the people your legacy will touch. Connection is built by sharing what you have — your talent, your time, your presence. A sundial in the shade serves no one. Step into the light. Be useful. That is how you build a life that outlasts you.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

